column1: Debug CAN mapping issue
column31:
This ticket has been created to account for the time invested in debugging a suspected NI issue. Despite using the same blue_marlin.dbc file, Zelos and Grafana are reporting different values for the same signals/messages.

For example, when there is no alarm on the system, Zelos is correctly reading 0 for the value of alarms latched. On the other hand, Grafana reports values between 1.41-1.43 when there is no alarm on the system. Also, some signals (particularly Manta signals) are not being reported on Grafana. Grafana obtains this data from the influxdB, which is also used to validate the plugin tests.

As a result, a lot of the scripts have been failing because the values of the signals used to validate the tests are either reporting incorrectly or not reported at all in Grafana. So the logic fails since the values don’t match. I am currently being supported by Raaga and Yung on this. 



*Zelos (Reporting correct value of 0 for alarms latched)*

!image-20240709-213305.png|width=1164,height=236,alt="image-20240709-213305.png"!



*Grafana/influxdB (Reporting incorrect value of 1.44 for alarms latched)*

!image-20240709-213249.png|width=404,height=242,alt="image-20240709-213249.png"!
column179:
10/Jul/24 8:08 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;Yung explained this is a known issue with NI where the registers are shifted and so the wrong values are read from the signals/messages.

Reloading and restarting the data acquisition using the curl commands several times fixes this issue, but only temporarily. The data acquisition often stops (especially after running a plugintest) and has to be started again. When restarted, the values reported in Grafana may be incorrect due to this NI issue. And it takes 1-3 reloads and restarts to fix it to report the correct values. That is when a plugintest can then be run. This process is very inconvenient, and Raaga and Yung have mentioned that improvements/changes to the framework will be implemented to address this issue.

Meanwhile, Yung has advised to update the PXI on Voltron to kernel 5.19. This is the version recommended by NI. This is the official tested version by NI so they want us to run on this and see if that issue still exists before next steps.

[~accountid:6421e9897222b08f3e733ba4]  for your visibility.

column1: Write Inverter metering accuracy test script
Write Operational Frequency Range Sweep test script
column179:
01/Jul/24 9:54 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;This script has been written and completed. Find it as ac_input_range_freq.go under the plugintests directory in the feature-voltron-dev branch of voltron.

In this script, the frequency on the chroma is changed to test that the inverter is operational when inside near the upper/lower boundaries of the IEEE acceptable AC frequency range. The trip time is measured by looping through the main relay state on the manta. This loop breaks only when the state changes; and a timer logic measures how long this takes.

To validate if the test passes/fails, the measured trip time is checked within a boundary. Now, the next step is to validate the script on the tester.

column31:
Write scripts to generate UDS model files in the format supported in the framework.

Update blue_marlin.dbc file in factorycommon.
column180:
24/Jun/24 4:23 PM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;3 different python scripts were written for each device to reformat the UDS files for our framework.

The feature-voltron branch of factorycommon has been updated with the latest UDS and DBC files. Retrieved from here: [bluemarlin-can/output at dbc/rc/20240611 · neurio/bluemarlin-can (github.com)|https://github.com/neurio/bluemarlin-can/tree/dbc/rc/20240611/output]
column181:
25/Jun/24 10:14 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;* I created python scripts in *Generate UDS files.zip* that will be useful to update the UDS data store model files for Blue Marlin releases. After Chris' team uploads the new yaml and dbc files with new FW releases, we will always have to update the data store model files in *data_store* under the *hal* directory in *factorycommon* to ensure our scripts function. See location below: 
!image-20240625-170949.png|width=38.04675716440422%,alt="image-20240625-170949.png"!
* I have updated this already with the latest from the *dbc/rc/20240611* branch in *bluemarlin-can*. [Link to page|https://github.com/neurio/bluemarlin-can/tree/dbc/rc/20240611/output].
* Generate UDS files contains 3 python files (bmuExportMap.py, bmuExportMap.py, and bmuExportMap.py) for each device to convert the yaml files uploaded by the CAN team to the format that is supported in the factory automation framework.
* To use these python scripts, download the yaml files for each device into the extracted folder containing the python scripts, and keep the same naming format. See screenshot below (left side) containing yaml files and python files in VScode.
!image-20240625-171007.png|width=54.7134238310709%,alt="image-20240625-171007.png"!
* To prevent the duplicate names, these scripts for each device only look at the "read_only: false" signals. This reformatting is for the UDS data store models, so we want to be able to write to the signals and keep the signals that state “read_only: false”. See screenshot below for example. In this instance, to prevent duplicates of “DERCAPACITY_SPECIFIED_OVEREXCITED_PF”, the generated script will parse for and *keep 40333* because of the “read_only: false” entry. Importantly, 40333 is better suited for UDS writes, while 40309 is read only. 
!image-20240626-181038.png|width=420,height=223,alt="image-20240626-181038.png"!
* Before running the scripts, check if yaml is installed. If yaml isn't already installed on your machine, install it using the commands below via the VScode terminal as it applies for your OS. You can also use these commands to check if it is already installed.Install commands YAML

{noformat}python -m pip install yaml (Windows)
sudo pip install yaml (Linux){noformat}

* Once installed, you can now run the scripts to generate the data store model files for the Blue Marlin devices. A go file will be created for each device after running each script. See the terminal box in the below screenshot for the commands to run the scripts. 
!image-20240625-171354.png|width=1060,height=730,alt="image-20240625-171354.png"!
* The go files created to hold the data store models for the devices will be saved in the same directory as the other files. See left side of the above screenshot. 
* Before updating factorycommon with the latest data store model files, first align with the SW team.

As a result, a lot of effort has been focused on troubleshooting the FW builds on this release.

This also impacted validating newly written automated tests, so we reverted to the previously approved RC’s to be able to do this. Meanwhile, more automated tests are being written and validated, and the code library is constantly being improved.

column179:
18/Jun/24 8:21 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;comp_enter_service has been completed, and just needs to be tested: 

* influxClient is implemented in the script to read CAN/analog signals. 
* The script validates the delay and ramp duration is within the allowed time for case 1 of the Enter Service test.
* The script is currently written to test and validate case 1 but can be easily modified to test case 5. {color:#ff5630}(There will be a future ticket created to create separate scripts for this).{color}
column181:
18/Jun/24 8:34 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;New sunspec_compliance.go file has been created in the voltron directory as a library with functions that configure the sunspec register configurations on the manta that will be needed to run compliance tests. 2 new functions (SunspecEsCaseOne & SunspecEsCaseFive) were created to initialize the UDS connection with the Manta and configure the sunspec registers on the Manta for testing case 1 and case 5 of the Enter Service test.

More functions will be added in sunspec_compliance.go as more compliance test scripts are written to configure the Manta for the test.

column1: BM-PreComp: Watt-Var
column31:
When in this mode, the DER shall actively control the reactive power output as a function of the active power output following a target piecewise linear active power-reactive power characteristic, without intentional time delay. *In no case, shall the response time be greater than 10 s.*



!watt-var 1 (4642a682-bb70-4d27-96f2-ce4c40e8b97a).png|width=1167,height=719,alt="watt-var 1.png"!

Below are parameters in the unit (SDS)

|Characteristics 1 DER set points| |Category|B| | |
|P1|P2|P3|P1'|P2'|P3'|
|1520|3800|7600|-1520|-3800|-7600|
|Q1|Q2|Q3|Q1'|Q2'|Q3'|
|0|0|-3344|0|0|3344|

Spot check: 

# run unit at nominal power with Watt-VAR feature turned on, ( Expected P = 11500, Expected Q= 5000 VAR, response time measured shall be less than 10 sec)
# command unit to 0 P ( Expected P = 0, Expected Q= 0, response time measured shall be less than 10 sec)
# command unit to output 4800 Watts ( Expected P = 4800 Watts, Expected Q= 0, response time measured shall be less than 10 sec)
# Command unit to output 11500 watts  ( Expected P = 4800 Watts, Expected Q= 0 ,response time measured shall be less than 10 sec)
# **verify on all above steps that open loop response time is met and reactive power expected is within +/-5% of Srated = +/-5% of 11500.

column1: BM-PreComp: Volt-Var
column31:
When in this mode, the DER shall actively control its reactive power output as a function of voltage
following a voltage-reactive power piecewise linear characteristic.



!Volt-Var 1 (2a84b0ff-7f57-4ca8-bb51-0005daba907a).png|width=1095,height=1125,alt="Volt-Var 1.png"!

The DER shall be capable of autonomously adjusting reference voltage (VRef) with VRef being equal to the
low pass filtered measured voltage. The time constant shall be adjustable at least over the range of 300 s to
5000 s. The voltage-reactive power Volt-Var curve characteristic shall be adjusted autonomously as VRef
changes.

Spot check:

# Enable VV mode with defaults as below and run unit at 100% Power (11500 Watts)

|Characteristics 1 set points| |Category|B| |
|V1|V2|V3|V4|Open loop response time Tr (s)|
|220.8|235.2|244.8|259.2|2.5|
|Q1|Q2|Q3|Q4|Vref|
|5082|0|0|-5082|240|

   2. Step AC grid sim to 252 ( Expected VAR= -2541)

   3. Step AC grid sim to 262.8 ( Expected VAr= -5082)

   4. Step AC grid sim to 231.6 (Expected VAR= 1143)

   5. Step AC grid sim to 214.8,  (Expected VAR= 5082)

** verify on all above steps that open loop response time is met and reactive power expected is within +/-5% of Srated = +/-5% of 11500.

column1: BM-PreComp: Limitations of DC Injection for Inverter
column31: Check during normal operation at full power, DC component is <0.24A

column1: BM-PreComp: Normal Ramp
column31:
This test confirms that an inverter meets a given response characteristic for providing ramp
rate responses for normal and/or soft-start ramp rate commands. An EUT can change the rate at which
they increase their power output. These ramp rates are constrained by what the systems can physically
do. For instance, if they are outputting their maximum power, they cannot ramp up, while a completely
charged storage system may discharge power into the Area EPS, but cannot draw power from the area
EPS as it is already completely charged.

 

Normal ramp-up rate when the inverter is adjusting the output power, e.g., when a PV inverter is
following the available power from the dc source.

 

Spot check:

1. Set normal ramp rate to 100 sec in unit.

2. Operate grid sim at nominal voltage (240V) and frequency (60Hz) and turn the unit on.

3. Unit shall follow a ramp of 100 seconds to reach at full power.

column1: BM-PreComp: Persistence of DER Settings
column31:
The purpose of this test is to confirm that DER parameter settings persist following a power cycle of the
DER.

 

Spot check: ( @Seun Osiyemi )

a) Select VV default values given in table below for the test and input that to Unit.
b) Adjust the three parameters to values that are within their respective ranges of adjustability
specified in IEEE Std 1547 and that differ from their respective initial and default values. ( for example: Vref originally wa set to 1, now change that to 0.95, Vref adjustime tieme const was initially set to 300 , now change it to 500 sec, open loop response time was initially set to 1, now change it to 5 sec) Verify
that the new values have been implemented. Record the new values.
c) Power cycle the DER or DER control component responsible for storing parameter settings. The
power cycle shall consist of removing ac test source voltage and disconnecting EUT input source
power or shutting down EUT generation and verifying that voltage at the control component
responsible for storing parameter settings has been removed for at least 60 s.
d) Restore power to the DER and/or controller.
e) Check and record the values of the parameters adjusted in step b).
 !image-2024-06-17-13-54-36-887.png|thumbnail!

column1: BM-PreComp: Constant Reactive Power
column31:
* When in this mode, the DER shall maintain a constant reactive power. The target reactive power level and
mode (injection or absorption) shall be specified by the Area EPS operator and shall be within the range
specified in 5.2 (44% required for Category-B, see snip below). The reactive power settings are allowed to be adjusted locally and/or remotely as specified by the Area EPS operator. The maximum DER response time to maintain constant reactive power shall be
10 s or less.
* Unit shall be able to provide reactive power at all DC ranges ( 360V- 420V)

Spot check: 

# Set ac grid sim to 240V, 60Hz and command unit to 20%Prated and enable constant VAR mode. DC range- 360VDC
# Command unit to 50%Prated (5750Watts)
# Command unit to 100%Prated (11500Watts) { Q exepected = 5000 VAR, P will reduce to 10000 Watts)
# Set grid sim to 214.8V  { Q exepected = 5000 VAR, P will reduce to 10000 Watts)
# Set grid sim to 260.4V { Q exepected = 5500 VAR, P will reduce to 10000 Watts)
# Set grid sim to 214.8V { Q exepected = 5000 VAR, P will reduce to 10000 Watts)
# Set grid sim to 240V  { Q exepected = 5000 VAR, P will reduce to 10000 Watts)
# **verify on all above steps that open loop response time is met and reactive power expected is within +/-5% of Srated = +/-5% of 11500.

column179:
21/Jun/24 9:42 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;This script has been written and completed. Find it as comp_ac_open_phase.go under the plugintests directory in the feature-voltron-dev branch of voltron.

In this script, the trip time to detect the open phase is measured by looping through the main relay state on the manta. This loop is breaks only when the state changes; and a timer logic measures how long this takes. The voltage on the open phase is also measured to ensure the phase is open.

To validate if the test passes/fails, the measured trip time is checked within a boundary. If the trip time is greater than 3 secs, the test fails. Now, the next step is to validate the script on the tester.

BM-PreComp: Constant Power Factor
column31:
When in this mode, the DER shall operate at a constant power factor. *The target power factor shall be*
*specified by the Area EPS operator and shall not require reactive power exceeding the reactive capability*
*requirements specified in 5.2 (44% for Category-B).* The power factor settings are allowed to be adjusted locally and/or remotely
as specified by the Area EPS operator. *The maximum DER response time to maintain constant power*
*factor shall be 10 s or less.*

Spot check: 

* Enable constant power factor mode and set the EUT power factor to PFmin,inj. ( 0.9 PF) Wait for steady state to be reached.

* Step the EUT’s active power to Pmin. (5% Prated)

* Step the EUT’s available active power to Prated. (11500 Watts)

* Step the ac test source voltage to 107.4 (each phase)

*  Step the ac test source voltage to 130.2 (each phase)

*  Step the ac test source voltage to 107.4 (each phase)

* Step ac test source voltage to 120 (240V split phase)

Expected PF at each step is 0.9 unless power factor mode is turned off.

BM-PreComp: HLVRT
column31:
The EUT shall be considered in compliance if it meets all the following requirements:

* Where the operating mode is specified as Permissive Operation, the EUT may Cease to Energize or may continue to exchange current with the ac test source. 
* The EUT shall ride through and shall not trip during Permissive Operation. If the operating mode of the EUT during Permissive Operation is Cease to Energize, the EUT shall comply with the Restore Output requirements as below:
** If the DER rides through a voltage disturbance without trip and the DER does not provide dynamic voltage support while in a mandatory operation or permissive operation region, once the applicable voltage surpasses the lower value of the mandatory operation region during low-voltage ride-through or the applicable voltage returns below the upper value of the continuous operation region during high-voltage ride-through, the DER.
*** Shall maintain synchronism with the Area EPS.
*** Shall restore output of active current to at least 80% of pre-disturbance active current level within 0.4 s. Active and reactive current oscillations in the post-disturbance period that are positively damped are acceptable.
* Where the operating mode is specified as Momentary Cessation, the EUT shall cease to exchange current with the resistive load bank or ac test source. Following the momentary cessation event the EUT shall comply with the Restore Output requirements as above.
* Active and reactive current oscillations that are positively damped are permitted during the disturbance and post-disturbance period.



Spot Check for LVRT:

*Transient type is STEP ( No SWEEP or rise/fall time between 2 test points)

|Voltage Setting in Grid Simulator|90%|2%|25%|52%|90%|2%|25%|52%|90%|2%|25%|52%|90%|90%|2%|54%|90%|
|Time Setting in Grid Simulator|5|1|9|10|5|1|9|10|5|1|9|10|120|5|1|9|120|



Spot Check for HVRT:

| |Voltage setting in Grid simulator|108%|119%|108%|119%|108%|119%|108%|108%|115%|108%|
| |time setting in grid simulator|5|12|5|12|5|12|120|5|12|120|
| |Transient Type ( Step is no sweep between one step to another)|Step|Step|Step|Step|Step|Step|Step|Step|Step|Step|

column31:
Penguin 2.1 serial communication is not working when connected to manta proto8. I tried with 2 different penguin 2.1 and both do not work with manta. 

Checked the harness and all pins are one to one (manta to penguin) so harness configuration is correct. 

I used 24V, GND, CANHI, and CANLO from the can bus to power penguin and I was able to see serial comms. 

Next check is to remove the reset connection from manta to penguin to make sure manta is not sending reset commands to penguin constantly.

column1: Assist with Penguin2 Programming
column31:
In three weeks, Penguin2 manufacturing will resume. In order to be prepared the following items will need to be addressed:

Penguin2 Provisioning: Currently stuck due to Celestica’s firewall rules

Penguin2 Rebooting: The 5V from USB allows the penguin to stay powered. This is problematic, as a full reboot is required to gather the MAC address following any non-flashing access of the UART port

Penguin2 Firmware Version Check: This is trivial to implement, the login page for the penguin2 on  bootup shows its current FW version.

Blue Marlin FW Release Testing: June 2024
column31:
Execution of the release test set and pre-compliance test set for Blue Marlin System FW received in June 20th, 2024.
The release candidates tested are:
Manta: 0.9.5 - RC2, RC3
BMU: 0.2.1-RC1, RC2, RC3
INV: 1.10.0-RC2, RC-4
This testing is done to close the loop on these release candidates and ensure stable and reliable FW for alpha sites, test systems, and production.
column109: 24-Q2-KR7.2: Validate BM Firmware Release in 48 Hours
column179:
26/Jun/24 7:34 AM;5e6aa6b89abcc30ce60ca4ef;we are currently blocked on release testing with a [Inverter bug|https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fgeneracet.atlassian.net%2Fbrowse%2FR2IF-322&data=05%7C02%7CJoe.Wardwell%40generac.com%7C939309b4eb5e4ff2d75708dc95d9051d%7C3a720757c2fd40b096eb840507006544%7C0%7C0%7C638550006545504768%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&sdata=dLorGtAFf45KQlFdaYi5zQbFfCoWByfwh7m%2FADOZJB4%3D&reserved=0] that won’t allow our systems to enable without an undervoltage alarm. This has been present on all RCs we have tested. This issue was repeated on both systems in Waukesha, and we are actively debugging the issue with Tony N.'s help. Details and links to the issue are in our [Issue Summary|https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fgeneracet.atlassian.net%2Fwiki%2Fspaces%2FCTET%2Fpages%2F403570689%2FR2%2BFW%2B-%2BJune%2B24%23Issue-Summary&data=05%7C02%7CJoe.Wardwell%40generac.com%7C939309b4eb5e4ff2d75708dc95d9051d%7C3a720757c2fd40b096eb840507006544%7C0%7C0%7C638550006545515929%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&sdata=japYCXUhJgtb%2FAOdCidSrYByB8uFT%2FssmiZ7sfK0gw4%3D&reserved=0] as well.

When we got to the end of our debugging sessions today without a resolution, so we rolled back FW on INV and BMU on our Voltron system to run more automated tests and continue to build out/improve/validate them.
Debugging continues the other system we have in Waukesha. When we get a procedure to correct this issue, or a new RC is available we will bring both systems back up to the release and continue testing.
